<a class="definition-word" data-category="general-biology" id="escherichia_coli_e_coli"><em>Escherichia coli (E. coli)</em></a> - A family of <a href="#bacteria">bacteria</a>. Certain <a href="#strain">strains</a> of <em>E. coli</em> are favoured by scientist in labs, most often the <a href="#e_coli_escherichia_coli_k12_strain"><em>K12 strain</em></a>. Some <a href="#strain">strains</a> of <em>E. coli,</em> can be <a href="#pathogenic">pathogenic</a> to humans. They have a small, ~4.6 <a href="#base_pair_bp">megabasepair</a> circular genome, are easily <a href="#transformation">transformed</a>, and replicate fast. Cell replication can be made to be limited by controlling <a href="#dna_desoxyribonucleic_acid">DNA</a> replication through predetermined growth conditions.